WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.060 --> 00:00:06.660
ANJALI KUMAR: Please join me
in welcoming to Google New

00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:07.751
York, Jacques Pepin.

00:00:07.751 --> 00:00:08.242
JACQUES PEPIN: Thank you.

00:00:08.242 --> 00:00:09.715
Thank you very much.

00:00:12.670 --> 00:00:13.720
ANJALI KUMAR: Thank you
so much for coming.

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:14.570
It's a thrill to have you.

00:00:14.570 --> 00:00:15.700
JACQUES PEPIN: Google
not exist when I

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:16.750
moved to New York.

00:00:16.750 --> 00:00:18.180
ANJALI KUMAR: Google didn't
exist when I moved to New

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:20.720
York, I think, either.

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:22.196
JACQUES PEPIN: None of
you existed when I

00:00:22.196 --> 00:00:24.310
moved to New York.

00:00:24.310 --> 00:00:26.800
It was 1959.

00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:30.770
So I wasn't kidding, you see.

00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:32.680
ANJALI KUMAR: Well, so now,
this tome that we talked

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:35.840
about, which, truly, I think,
does weigh more than my child.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:36.920
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:00:36.920 --> 00:00:38.580
ANJALI KUMAR: It was originally
two books.

00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:39.055
JACQUES PEPIN: That's
not "Cuisine

00:00:39.055 --> 00:00:41.988
Master." It's very heavy.

00:00:41.988 --> 00:00:42.450
ANJALI KUMAR: Yes, it is.

00:00:42.450 --> 00:00:43.970
JACQUES PEPIN: It's
not light cuisine.

00:00:43.970 --> 00:00:44.410
ANJALI KUMAR: Pardon?

00:00:44.410 --> 00:00:45.310
JACQUES PEPIN: It's
not light cuisine.

00:00:45.310 --> 00:00:45.950
It's very heavy.

00:00:45.950 --> 00:00:47.030
ANJALI KUMAR: No, it's
heavy cuisine.

00:00:47.030 --> 00:00:49.585
So it was originally two books,
"La Technique" and "La

00:00:49.585 --> 00:00:53.280
Methode" that you originally
wrote in the late '70s.

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:53.640
JACQUES PEPIN: Right.

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:54.800
ANJALI KUMAR: So can you tell
us a little bit about the

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:57.690
inspiration for the original
two books and then why you

00:00:57.690 --> 00:00:58.980
decided to combine them?

00:00:58.980 --> 00:00:59.420
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah.

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:02.440
Actually, I had a friend of
mine who kind of became a

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:03.820
surrogate mother.

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:05.200
Her name was Helen McCully.

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:07.930
She was the food editor of
McCall's "House Beautiful." I

00:01:07.930 --> 00:01:10.630
lived on 50th and 1st
Avenue at the time.

00:01:10.630 --> 00:01:11.910
ANJALI KUMAR: We're all going
to show up tomorrow.

00:01:11.910 --> 00:01:12.910
JACQUES PEPIN: And she--

00:01:12.910 --> 00:01:13.940
ANJALI KUMAR: There's
going to be a line.

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:17.330
JACQUES PEPIN: And I
started writing.

00:01:17.330 --> 00:01:19.300
She always pushed me--

00:01:19.300 --> 00:01:20.690
do this, do that.

00:01:20.690 --> 00:01:22.780
Don't put those stupid socks
we have in front.

00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:24.240
Don't do this don't do that.

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:27.790
An then I started doing little
things for "House Beautiful,"

00:01:27.790 --> 00:01:29.110
and I say you know what
would be good?

00:01:29.110 --> 00:01:30.760
Is to show people
how to do it.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:32.460
So we decided to do pictures.

00:01:32.460 --> 00:01:35.470
Those were pictures in black and
white about the size of a

00:01:35.470 --> 00:01:38.090
stamp, so you couldn't
see anything.

00:01:38.090 --> 00:01:40.200
And so that was the beginning
of that book.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:44.860
And I met a friend of mine,
Craig LaBan, the food editor

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:48.007
of the "New York Times." I
went to his house in East

00:01:48.007 --> 00:01:50.920
Hampton, and there I
met Herb Nagourney.

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:55.410
He was the president of the "New
York Times" book company

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:56.480
called Quadrangle.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:57.850
And he said, do you want
to do a book with us?

00:01:57.850 --> 00:02:00.070
I said, yeah, I'd love to.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:02.630
So I started, and I said, well,
you know, maybe I need

00:02:02.630 --> 00:02:03.880
like 400 pictures.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:06.030
And I called him, and I
said, maybe like 800.

00:02:06.030 --> 00:02:07.730
He said, OK, go ahead.

00:02:07.730 --> 00:02:09.289
I said, like 1,200?

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:10.340
He said, OK, fine.

00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:10.935
Like 1,500?

00:02:10.935 --> 00:02:12.170
He said OK.

00:02:12.170 --> 00:02:13.800
1,500, that's enough.

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:17.080
So I did a book, about 1,500
pictures, and I did a second

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:20.790
one, which we didn't want to
call "La Technique Number

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:24.000
Two," so we find a synonym and
called it "La Methode," and

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.060
that was a continuation
of this.

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:28.320
And those books were in print
for many, many years.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:32.600
And about 12 years ago, I
reorganized the material, too,

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.780
and we did a large
book out of it.

00:02:34.780 --> 00:02:39.080
And then this year, we, again,
reorganized the material and

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:42.970
took a lot of pictures in color
that I have in a book

00:02:42.970 --> 00:02:47.780
called "The Art of Cooking,
Volume 1 and 2" that I did in

00:02:47.780 --> 00:02:50.090
the end of the '80s, which
is probably the best

00:02:50.090 --> 00:02:51.340
book that I've done.

00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:55.600
We're reorganizing and reusing
those pictures in there.

00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:59.290
interestingly enough, I have
some book, after like 8, 10

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:02.330
years, people look at it, and
they say, well, we can't

00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:02.970
really use it.

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:04.540
The pictures are obsolete.

00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:06.320
Technology goes so fast.

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:08.820
And it's true that there
is a certain style.

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:13.800
Like a few years ago, where you
would kind of focus on the

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:17.430
main dish to shoot a picture
and make it very clear, and

00:03:17.430 --> 00:03:20.620
all the outside kind of
cloudy and in a moody

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:22.630
and a romantic way.

00:03:22.630 --> 00:03:27.380
That was a style of shooting
which can date the picture,

00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:27.950
pretty much.

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:31.200
But that doesn't happen with
this, because those are just a

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:34.690
close-up of my hand boning
a chicken, turning a

00:03:34.690 --> 00:03:35.450
thing, and so forth.

00:03:35.450 --> 00:03:37.330
So that's why they didn't
get obsolete.

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:40.910
And the point is that the
technique, the way you beat an

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:43.190
egg white, or peel an asparagus,
bone out an

00:03:43.190 --> 00:03:46.530
chicken, make an omelette, or
do a caramel cage, it's the

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:48.810
same now that it was
50 years ago.

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:51.120
I am Dean of Study at the French
Culinary Institute

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:56.400
here, and we have what they call
the Competency, like 250,

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:57.870
which are like techniques
that we have to

00:03:57.870 --> 00:03:59.830
cover, like doing eggs.

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.080
You have to know how to do
scrambled eggs, poached eggs,

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:03.160
this, this, and that.

00:04:03.160 --> 00:04:06.730
With the poached eggs, we do it
now the same way we did 50

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:10.030
years ago, except 50 years ago
without all this sauce and

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:12.510
some truffle on top, of a piece
of ham underneath, a

00:04:12.510 --> 00:04:15.180
bouche, so that was
the Eggs Benedict.

00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:19.079
And now you may do your eggs
with a little tiny asparagus

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:22.450
hedge, or saute in a much more
modern way, but basically the

00:04:22.450 --> 00:04:24.690
techniques themselves
don't change.

00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:25.610
ANJALI KUMAR: Right.

00:04:25.610 --> 00:04:28.140
So why did you feel the
need to combine

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:30.190
these into one volume?

00:04:30.190 --> 00:04:31.260
JACQUES PEPIN: To sell
more and make money.

00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:33.650
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:33.650 --> 00:04:35.210
ANJALI KUMAR: That's
very smart of you.

00:04:35.210 --> 00:04:39.560
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, I have
a series on television now

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:44.060
called "Essential Pepin," which
I taped last year, or

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:45.340
started last year.

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:50.200
And I have a book, and what
makes it in the book is I have

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:56.030
a three and half hours DVD of
technique, a great deal of the

00:04:56.030 --> 00:04:57.020
technique that I
have in there.

00:04:57.020 --> 00:04:58.730
And, in fact, when they
say, well, we want

00:04:58.730 --> 00:05:01.230
to redo that book.

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:02.980
We want to do something
different too.

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:06.430
And at that point, I said it'd
be great if you do that.

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:07.530
A DVD going with it?

00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:08.710
I said, that's great.

00:05:08.710 --> 00:05:10.200
I just did one for
the other book.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:12.720
So they said, well, can
you do one there?

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:15.200
I said no, it would
be redundant.

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:19.090
So this is basically what
I have in there, here.

00:05:19.090 --> 00:05:23.360
And, frankly, I teach at Boston
University for about 30

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:25.060
years and at the
French Culinary

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:27.150
Institute here in New York.

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:32.400
Those schools, you go, and it's
like $40,000, $45,000 for

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:33.670
the program.

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:36.970
And basically all of that is
on that three-hours tape.

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:39.690
I mean, not all of it, but a
great deal of the technique.

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:40.580
ANJALI KUMAR: Shh.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:40.870
Don't tell anyone.

00:05:40.870 --> 00:05:41.820
JACQUES PEPIN: So it's
just amazing.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:43.080
ANJALI KUMAR: Boston University
is not going to be

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:45.410
happy with you right now when
they hear this tape.

00:05:45.410 --> 00:05:45.908
JACQUES PEPIN: No, no.

00:05:45.908 --> 00:05:47.900
Oh, well.

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:49.780
No, we do some good
classes, there.

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:53.490
I was there last week with a
group of like 10 people.

00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:59.320
I do your participation class
and participation class and

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:01.820
demonstration, which I do
demonstration usually.

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:07.490
But there, I do like the perfect
meal for me-- a roast

00:06:07.490 --> 00:06:09.400
chicken, a boiled
potato, a salad.

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:11.890
But just with an exactly
one certain way to--

00:06:11.890 --> 00:06:15.660
so I can do it, the student
did it, and then they go

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:17.820
behind the stove, each one with
a chicken, and then they

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:20.990
redo it for the class and
they'll make like five hours.

00:06:20.990 --> 00:06:26.660
And that's what I tell
them, very often.

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:28.910
Don't try to blow my mind
and make something

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:30.290
different with it.

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:31.360
Cook with your guts.

00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:34.270
In some way, you cannot escape
yourself anyway.

00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:36.270
And for the better or
for the worse, you

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:38.080
have 15 people here.

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:40.630
I am going to have 15
different chickens--

00:06:40.630 --> 00:06:43.750
two undercooked, two overcooked,
two burned, one

00:06:43.750 --> 00:06:45.560
cold, two hot, and so forth.

00:06:45.560 --> 00:06:48.850
But they will be different,
because you really cannot cook

00:06:48.850 --> 00:06:50.390
like the person next to you.

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:51.910
You are not that person.

00:06:51.910 --> 00:06:54.470
And so that's important.

00:06:54.470 --> 00:06:56.730
ANJALI KUMAR: You wear so many
different hats in your life,

00:06:56.730 --> 00:06:59.380
and have, throughout your
career, everything from being

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:02.800
the dean of various schools,
various cooking institutions,

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:05.180
to writing all these books
and the television shows.

00:07:05.180 --> 00:07:07.420
Which has been your favorite
thing to do?

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:09.310
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, all
of it, in a sense.

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:12.170
I get bored if I have to
do the same thing.

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:14.955
I had a column in the "New York
Times" for like 10 years

00:07:14.955 --> 00:07:16.650
in the '80s.

00:07:16.650 --> 00:07:19.880
If you only have to do that,
you're always pressured by one

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:21.900
thing or another or a
book and so forth.

00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.840
But I go teaching, or
I confuse that at

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:26.110
the Russian Tea Room.

00:07:26.110 --> 00:07:28.560
I opened the World Trade Center
here in the Hilton.

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:31.220
So it's a type of work, then
you go back to doing an

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:34.190
article for this,
then I teach.

00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:37.550
That's the beauty of doing all
things related to food, but

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:38.720
different things.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.830
But to a certain extent,
probably teaching, I like.

00:07:41.830 --> 00:07:43.930
ANJALI KUMAR: Well, so, you were
on a much loved show with

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:46.080
Julia Child, "Julia
and Jacques."

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.634
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:07:48.634 --> 00:07:50.900
ANJALI KUMAR: There seems like
there's stories there.

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:52.680
And you guys were really the
pioneers of the sort of

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:56.340
television chef and the sort of
celebritization of chefs.

00:07:56.340 --> 00:07:58.360
Can you tell us a bit
about your favorite

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:00.150
memories with Julia?

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:03.860
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, there's
so many memories.

00:08:03.860 --> 00:08:06.310
I met Julia in 1960.

00:08:06.310 --> 00:08:09.410
And we became friends.

00:08:09.410 --> 00:08:12.150
And then we cooked together
very occasionally.

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:15.340
And when I started teaching at
BU, I would always see her

00:08:15.340 --> 00:08:19.210
from breakfast, to lunch, to
late-night drink, or whatever,

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:21.690
with Julia.

00:08:21.690 --> 00:08:23.710
And at some point,
I said, maybe we

00:08:23.710 --> 00:08:25.450
should do a PBS special.

00:08:25.450 --> 00:08:28.710
And we did at BU what we called
"Cooking in Concert,"

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:32.370
for that two-hour show that we
taped in the Tsai Auditorium

00:08:32.370 --> 00:08:35.200
at BU, and which was shown--

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:38.289
that was just prior to the Food
Channel Network, which

00:08:38.289 --> 00:08:41.309
was widely shown on PBS.

00:08:41.309 --> 00:08:45.340
And then that led us to do
another two-hour special, and

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:48.420
eventually, we did the
series together.

00:08:48.420 --> 00:08:50.400
Conventionally, when
you do a series--

00:08:50.400 --> 00:08:53.020
I have done some with my
daughter, Claudine.

00:08:53.020 --> 00:08:57.470
I have done 12 series of 26
shows, mostly with KQED, the

00:08:57.470 --> 00:08:59.510
PBS station in San Francisco.

00:08:59.510 --> 00:09:03.760
But I remember doing a series
years ago which was on time,

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:05.870
so a 30-minute show
with like 28 and a

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:07.350
half minutes, whatever.

00:09:07.350 --> 00:09:09.790
So I have like three dishes
or four dishes to do.

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:13.470
And there's a guy going back
with a sign-- nine minutes,

00:09:13.470 --> 00:09:16.960
six minutes, five, three,
one, 30 seconds,

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:18.250
wrap up, and so forth.

00:09:18.250 --> 00:09:19.920
It can be a bit stressful.

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:22.430
You want to look kind of
suave and go and the

00:09:22.430 --> 00:09:24.060
thing has to be finished.

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:26.850
So when I started doing some
with Claudine, my daughter, I

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:30.460
say, you know, I'm supposed to
teach the kid how to cook, and

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:33.730
if I show her how to make a
pie, and she's rolling the

00:09:33.730 --> 00:09:36.390
dough and struggling, and the
guy goes back there, three

00:09:36.390 --> 00:09:39.800
minutes, I push the kid off
and grab the dough.

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:43.220
So I said, OK, well, don't
go to too long.

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:44.430
Editing is expensive.

00:09:44.430 --> 00:09:47.420
So we end up showing
35, 38 minutes.

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:49.630
They have to do editing
a little bit.

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:51.310
Then we did the show
with Julia.

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:53.270
And Julia said, you know,
we're going to cook.

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:55.770
When it's finished,
we'll tell you.

00:09:55.770 --> 00:09:56.560
We did some show--

00:09:56.560 --> 00:10:03.750
I think the longest one 120
minutes for a 30-minute show.

00:10:03.750 --> 00:10:05.220
And, of course, it was great.

00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:06.220
We kept drinking wine.

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:06.710
We cooked.

00:10:06.710 --> 00:10:07.840
OK, it's over.

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:09.000
Finished.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.560
And I am amazed sometimes at
seeing some of the show, where

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:14.680
it's very smooth and all that.

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:18.610
It wasn't that smooth at all,
and it was much too long.

00:10:18.610 --> 00:10:22.120
But that's the beauty of
anything, I suppose.

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:26.630
But PBS, Julia loves
to work for PBS.

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:32.640
All I do, we don't have
to cow to a sponsor

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:33.340
and stuff like that.

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:35.530
In fact, we don't even have
the right to work for a

00:10:35.530 --> 00:10:37.026
sponsor and all that.

00:10:37.026 --> 00:10:39.750
Not that I'm such
a great pure--

00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:41.630
if you pay me enough, I'll
work for anyone.

00:10:41.630 --> 00:10:42.550
But--

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:44.430
I'm kidding.

00:10:44.430 --> 00:10:47.610
But the point is Julia
was happy.

00:10:47.610 --> 00:10:51.270
So one time, I remember we had
Kendall Jackson came, and Jess

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:57.440
Jackson and his Barbara Banke
owned Cambria Winery, and he

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:01.010
owned Artisans &amp; Estates, which
is like 30 wineries--

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:03.740
Pepe, La Crema, Stonestreet
all of those.

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:05.070
So we had a lot of wine.

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:06.480
They were very nice people.

00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:08.280
He told me, you can have
any wine you want.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:10.660
Well, I didn't want to take the
Mondavi wine next to him,

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:12.470
but I had French wine,
and Italian,

00:11:12.470 --> 00:11:14.100
Spanish, Portuguese, whatever.

00:11:14.100 --> 00:11:15.320
South African.

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:21.070
And we started having a glass
of white wine, and we start

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:22.030
cooking, too.

00:11:22.030 --> 00:11:25.410
So they call and say we'd like
to come see a couple of shows

00:11:25.410 --> 00:11:28.710
taped, and maybe we will take
you out for dinner with Julia.

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:30.170
I said, terrific.

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:32.490
Because they became
friends with me.

00:11:32.490 --> 00:11:34.080
And so they came.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:38.130
They were in the room, the
control room, whatever, where

00:11:38.130 --> 00:11:39.570
you can see the show.

00:11:39.570 --> 00:11:43.690
And Jeff Drummond, the producer,
said well, Kendall

00:11:43.690 --> 00:11:44.395
Jackson is there--

00:11:44.395 --> 00:11:45.250
I mean, Jess Jackson.

00:11:45.250 --> 00:11:46.660
What are you going to do?

00:11:46.660 --> 00:11:46.980
And I said, Jackson?

00:11:46.980 --> 00:11:47.940
It's not like we don't
drink wine.

00:11:47.940 --> 00:11:48.560
Fine.

00:11:48.560 --> 00:11:49.360
We'll drink wine.

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:51.470
I don't know which we'll
drink, but we'll drink.

00:11:51.470 --> 00:11:56.440
So we finished the show, and I
even forget what we did, but I

00:11:56.440 --> 00:11:57.650
tell Julia, OK that's great.

00:11:57.650 --> 00:12:00.750
Do you want a little bit of
Cabernet Sauvignon with that

00:12:00.750 --> 00:12:02.000
or you want a Merlot?

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:02.505
She said [HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]

00:12:02.505 --> 00:12:03.391
I want beer.

00:12:03.391 --> 00:12:05.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:05.750 --> 00:12:06.980
JACQUES PEPIN: I said what do
you mean you want beer?

00:12:06.980 --> 00:12:08.650
I said, we don't have beer.

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:08.760
[HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:09.526
We have beer.

00:12:09.526 --> 00:12:10.776
She got beer underneath.

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:16.340
Well, I told Julia, I mean,
maybe we don't have to cow to

00:12:16.340 --> 00:12:17.685
the sponsor, but we
don't really have

00:12:17.685 --> 00:12:18.650
to antagonize them.

00:12:18.650 --> 00:12:21.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:21.470 --> 00:12:23.600
JACQUES PEPIN: And then she did
the same thing with the

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:25.800
president of Land
O'Lakes came.

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:28.250
I mean, it's not like we
didn't use butter.

00:12:28.250 --> 00:12:29.074
She said [HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]

00:12:29.074 --> 00:12:29.898
more butter, boom.

00:12:29.898 --> 00:12:32.860
She put another stick of butter,
two sticks of butter.

00:12:32.860 --> 00:12:35.580
So we did, and so the producer
said, what are

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:36.140
you going to do?

00:12:36.140 --> 00:12:39.500
I said, Jeff, I'm doing a dough,
and I'm going to do a

00:12:39.500 --> 00:12:41.980
tart with it, a big gullet.

00:12:41.980 --> 00:12:44.070
And then, with the rest of them,
I'll show them how to

00:12:44.070 --> 00:12:47.520
cover a dish to do a chicken
pot pie or whatever.

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:52.030
And we had no recipes on any
of the shows with Julia.

00:12:52.030 --> 00:12:54.380
So at the last moment, we'd
change, or whatever.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:55.490
And so Julia said
[HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]

00:12:55.490 --> 00:12:58.020
I want to do my dough.

00:12:58.020 --> 00:12:58.630
I said fine.

00:12:58.630 --> 00:12:59.560
You want to do your dough.

00:12:59.560 --> 00:13:00.420
OK, fine.

00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:02.420
So I started.

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:04.650
I made the dough, rolled
it, put that.

00:13:04.650 --> 00:13:07.925
And I said, now, Julia is going
to show you how to do

00:13:07.925 --> 00:13:08.770
another dough.

00:13:08.770 --> 00:13:09.750
She said [HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]

00:13:09.750 --> 00:13:13.560
well, Jacques is going to
do it, which she did.

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:15.610
So I said, OK, fine.

00:13:15.610 --> 00:13:17.410
She said I want you to do
it in a food processor.

00:13:17.410 --> 00:13:18.355
I say, OK.

00:13:18.355 --> 00:13:20.440
I take the food processor,
I said all right.

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:24.030
A couple of cups of flour, a
dash of sugar, a dash of salt.

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:25.060
I said how much butter
she wanted.

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:25.445
She said [HIGH-PITCHED VOICE]

00:13:25.445 --> 00:13:27.346
I want Crisco.

00:13:27.346 --> 00:13:29.060
You want Crisco?

00:13:29.060 --> 00:13:30.950
The president of to Land
O'Lakes is there.

00:13:30.950 --> 00:13:31.930
We have no Crisco.

00:13:31.930 --> 00:13:32.800
We never use--

00:13:32.800 --> 00:13:34.580
she had a can of Crisco
underneath.

00:13:34.580 --> 00:13:38.560
She grabs it, and we did half
butter, half Crisco oil.

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:40.260
That was Julia.

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:42.670
ANJALI KUMAR: I was going to ask
you to do an impression of

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:44.050
Julia Child, but I feel like--

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:44.460
JACQUES PEPIN: Oh, OK.

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:46.580
ANJALI KUMAR: --we've already
been treated to one.

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:48.780
You do a very good
Julia Child.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:49.010
JACQUES PEPIN: Not really.

00:13:49.010 --> 00:13:51.050
Not as good as my daughter.

00:13:51.050 --> 00:13:54.920
When my daughter was born, I
already knew Julia Child,

00:13:54.920 --> 00:13:57.550
which is a long time, because
Claudine is going to be 45.

00:13:57.550 --> 00:13:58.500
Whew!

00:13:58.500 --> 00:14:04.290
In any case, I talked often on
the telephone with Julia, and

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:07.650
Claudine, my daughter, ended
up doing a very good

00:14:07.650 --> 00:14:08.800
imitation of Julia.

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:10.010
I mean, terrific.

00:14:10.010 --> 00:14:11.720
And she used to do that
all the time.

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:14.320
And she went to college at BU.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:16.430
That's why I'm teaching there.

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:19.600
So she went to BU, so
she used to call.

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:23.290
One time I'm eating dinner
with my wife, and the

00:14:23.290 --> 00:14:23.410
telephone rang.

00:14:23.410 --> 00:14:24.470
Gloria picked up
the telephone.

00:14:24.470 --> 00:14:27.070
She'd say, OK, Claudine,
well, what do you want?

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:27.950
Stop fooling around.

00:14:27.950 --> 00:14:28.450
What do you want?

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:30.160
And now she'd say, oh, no, no.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:31.220
I'm sorry, Julia.

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:31.710
I'm sorry.

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:33.360
I'll call him right away.

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:37.790
She thought it was Claudine
doing her imitation of Julia.

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:39.040
So she was good.

00:14:41.510 --> 00:14:42.740
ANJALI KUMAR: Well, I'm going
to do a couple of "finish

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:46.270
these sentences" with you,
because there's a lot of

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:48.400
people here that I know have
questions that are going to be

00:14:48.400 --> 00:14:50.400
better than anything
I can come up with.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:52.950
We've already chatted on the way
in, so I want to make sure

00:14:52.950 --> 00:14:54.100
we leave some time
for everybody.

00:14:54.100 --> 00:14:54.660
JACQUES PEPIN: All right.

00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:56.520
ANJALI KUMAR: So those of you
who do have questions, please

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:58.750
get ready to go to one of the
mics, because we are recording

00:14:58.750 --> 00:15:00.520
this for YouTube.

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:02.600
So I'll just ask you to finish
the sentence that I'm going to

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:03.413
read to you.

00:15:03.413 --> 00:15:04.360
JACQUES PEPIN: All right.

00:15:04.360 --> 00:15:06.000
ANJALI KUMAR: The most essential
technique to learn

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:07.920
the kitchen is?

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:09.900
JACQUES PEPIN: Is how to
drink wine properly.

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:10.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:10.300 --> 00:15:11.550
JACQUES PEPIN: You have to--

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:14.480
ANJALI KUMAR: Well, so
now, you were at a

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:15.690
wine event this morning.

00:15:15.690 --> 00:15:16.820
Can you tell us about that?

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:18.850
JACQUES PEPIN: This morning
I was introduced at the

00:15:18.850 --> 00:15:21.450
Companion de Beaujolais.

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:23.620
I am from Beaujolais, actually,
in France, and the

00:15:23.620 --> 00:15:26.830
Beaujolais Nouveau, the new
Beaujolais, start on the 15th

00:15:26.830 --> 00:15:28.330
of November every year.

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:29.590
So they came this morning.

00:15:29.590 --> 00:15:35.110
We went down Park Avenue with
the guy on the trumpet playing

00:15:35.110 --> 00:15:37.650
"When the Saint Go Marching
In" and we had a bottle of

00:15:37.650 --> 00:15:38.790
Beaujolais.

00:15:38.790 --> 00:15:41.662
So I had some this
morning, too.

00:15:41.662 --> 00:15:43.060
I feel all right.

00:15:43.060 --> 00:15:47.340
But Anjali gave me a sandwich
and a banana, a couple of fig.

00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:47.450
ANJALI KUMAR: I know.

00:15:47.450 --> 00:15:49.310
We treat our guests well here.

00:15:49.310 --> 00:15:50.010
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:15:50.010 --> 00:15:51.020
ANJALI KUMAR: You didn't
bring me any wine,

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:51.750
but we'll talk about--

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:53.520
JACQUES PEPIN: Google
sandwich is amazing.

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:54.930
ANJALI KUMAR: It was
good, right?

00:15:54.930 --> 00:15:55.296
JACQUES PEPIN: Whoo!

00:15:55.296 --> 00:15:55.420
Incredible.

00:15:55.420 --> 00:15:56.150
ANJALI KUMAR: A ham sandwich.

00:15:56.150 --> 00:15:57.330
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:15:57.330 --> 00:15:58.690
ANJALI KUMAR: It goes nicely
with the Beaujolais.

00:15:58.690 --> 00:15:59.680
JACQUES PEPIN: Pam sandwich?

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:00.810
That what it was?

00:16:00.810 --> 00:16:01.120
ANJALI KUMAR: Ham.

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:02.840
JACQUES PEPIN: Oh, I thought
you said Pam.

00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:03.190
OK.

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:03.361
ANJALI KUMAR: No.

00:16:03.361 --> 00:16:04.300
Pam sandwich.

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:06.150
What would a Pam sandwich
entail?

00:16:06.150 --> 00:16:06.600
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah.

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:07.970
ANJALI KUMAR: Pam
like the spray?

00:16:07.970 --> 00:16:08.390
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah.

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:10.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:10.490 --> 00:16:13.160
JACQUES PEPIN: When you're
broke, you know--

00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:14.740
ANJALI KUMAR: It's a tight
budget here, that's true.

00:16:14.740 --> 00:16:16.010
But not that type.

00:16:16.010 --> 00:16:16.165
OK.

00:16:16.165 --> 00:16:17.010
Now finish the sentence.

00:16:17.010 --> 00:16:21.280
A food trends I hate is?

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:22.410
JACQUES PEPIN: Molecular
cooking.

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:22.670
Oh, no.

00:16:22.670 --> 00:16:24.040
I don't--

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:24.550
ANJALI KUMAR: You can say it.

00:16:24.550 --> 00:16:25.240
JACQUES PEPIN: I like
molecular cooking

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:25.850
for some time now.

00:16:25.850 --> 00:16:28.790
A trend that I hate--

00:16:28.790 --> 00:16:31.340
I can't think of any because
I'm a real glutton.

00:16:31.340 --> 00:16:34.500
So I eat anything you
put in front of me.

00:16:34.500 --> 00:16:36.850
ANJALI KUMAR: Including
a pam. sandwich.

00:16:36.850 --> 00:16:37.730
JACQUES PEPIN: Including
pam sandwich, yeah.

00:16:37.730 --> 00:16:39.540
ANJALI KUMAR: I'll remember
that for next time.

00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:41.910
My favorite kitchen tool is.

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:43.320
JACQUES PEPIN: My finger.

00:16:43.320 --> 00:16:46.710
I mean, there's nothing to
replace your finger.

00:16:46.710 --> 00:16:53.860
It squeezes, it crushes, it
strains, it twists, it kills.

00:16:53.860 --> 00:16:55.350
ANJALI KUMAR: All purpose.

00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:59.230
The thing I miss most
about France is?

00:16:59.230 --> 00:17:01.940
JACQUES PEPIN: Well,
my mother.

00:17:01.940 --> 00:17:02.950
She's still there.

00:17:02.950 --> 00:17:04.160
ANJALI KUMAR: Somebody's
laughing in the audience.

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:04.950
I'm not sure why.

00:17:04.950 --> 00:17:05.560
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah.

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:06.540
ANJALI KUMAR: I thought
that was sweet.

00:17:06.540 --> 00:17:07.825
JACQUES PEPIN: She's
98, though, so

00:17:07.825 --> 00:17:11.099
she's getting there.

00:17:11.099 --> 00:17:12.950
But I saw her this spring.

00:17:12.950 --> 00:17:14.980
I am Executive Culinary
Director of

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:18.020
Oceana cruise line.

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:21.040
So we do a couple of cruises a
year, and I tend to go to Lyon

00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:25.550
and see her and my cousin
and so forth.

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:27.539
And that's always fun.

00:17:27.539 --> 00:17:28.950
ANJALI KUMAR: That's nice.

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:31.330
If I wanted to impress
Julia Child, I

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:33.950
would have made blank.

00:17:33.950 --> 00:17:36.750
JACQUES PEPIN: I would have
given her the best one that I

00:17:36.750 --> 00:17:38.572
have in my cellar,
to start with and

00:17:38.572 --> 00:17:40.900
probably a ham sandwich.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:41.990
She loves ham.

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:45.290
I do love ham, too.

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:50.190
We have that book called "The
Last Meal of My Life,"

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:50.840
something like that.

00:17:50.840 --> 00:17:54.260
There are 50 chefs on it, and
they ask you what is the best

00:17:54.260 --> 00:17:54.880
thing you can eat.

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:58.520
And if you have the greatest,
greatest bread that I can

00:17:58.520 --> 00:18:03.370
think of and the greatest butter
that I can think of,

00:18:03.370 --> 00:18:07.060
it's very difficult to beat
bread and butter.

00:18:07.060 --> 00:18:08.220
It's true.

00:18:08.220 --> 00:18:11.040
That being said, I probably
will have squid with fresh

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:14.460
peas and maybe a can of caviar,
probably a hot dog.

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:15.820
Ham and egg I love.

00:18:15.820 --> 00:18:18.220
All that stuff are things
that I like.

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:21.830
But be sure that it would
be a very, very, very,

00:18:21.830 --> 00:18:24.500
very, very long meal.

00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:25.750
if it were to be the last one.

00:18:28.300 --> 00:18:29.510
ANJALI KUMAR: Well,
thank you so much.

00:18:29.510 --> 00:18:31.140
I think we're going to open
it up to questions

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:32.780
if anyone has any.

00:18:32.780 --> 00:18:36.106
JACQUES PEPIN: Preferably
about food and wine.

00:18:36.106 --> 00:18:38.560
ANJALI KUMAR: But anything.

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:40.030
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:18:40.030 --> 00:18:41.080
Do they need the mic, no?

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:42.400
ANJALI KUMAR: They need
to mic, yes, please.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:43.650
We're recording.

00:18:45.400 --> 00:18:46.520
JACQUES PEPIN: You're
recording this?

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:47.330
ANJALI KUMAR: We are.

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:48.050
JACQUES PEPIN: Oh my god.

00:18:48.050 --> 00:18:49.510
ANJALI KUMAR: I have to have
you sign a release.

00:18:49.510 --> 00:18:52.010
I have to remember to do that.

00:18:52.010 --> 00:18:52.280
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:54.920
So next week-- oh,
is this working?

00:18:54.920 --> 00:18:57.720
Next week, obviously, we have
Thanksgiving coming up, which

00:18:57.720 --> 00:19:00.390
is probably the biggest
food holiday.

00:19:00.390 --> 00:19:03.290
So I was wondering if there are
any particular culinary

00:19:03.290 --> 00:19:06.380
traditions that you liked
on Thanksgiving.

00:19:06.380 --> 00:19:08.700
JACQUES PEPIN: Did you see the
"New York Times" yesterday?

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:11.580
I had my turkey in the "New
York Times" yesterday.

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:18.800
And as I said in the article, I
haven't actually read it, be

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:21.620
the truth, so I don't
know what they cut

00:19:21.620 --> 00:19:22.840
out of what I wrote.

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:28.120
But certainly, I had my friend
Susie Heller, the producer of

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:29.970
the show for Julia
and so forth.

00:19:29.970 --> 00:19:34.310
Like 30 years ago, she lived
in Cleveland at the time.

00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:37.120
And she said, oh, I'm going
to the Thanksgiving.

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:37.970
I want you to come.

00:19:37.970 --> 00:19:39.190
And I said great.

00:19:39.190 --> 00:19:41.510
She said, I'm going to do
a big saddle of veal.

00:19:41.510 --> 00:19:42.200
Be different.

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:43.340
I said, what?

00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:45.710
I said, if you don't do
turkey, I'm not going.

00:19:45.710 --> 00:19:47.790
I mean, Thanksgiving
is turkey.

00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:52.880
So she got some turkey, and she
even went to a butcher.

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:53.690
She had a butcher.

00:19:53.690 --> 00:19:55.230
She had a fresh turkey.

00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:56.870
And she said, you have
something special?

00:19:56.870 --> 00:20:00.700
Could you get some turkey
fried for me?

00:20:00.700 --> 00:20:01.410
And the butcher--

00:20:01.410 --> 00:20:01.740
ANJALI KUMAR: Wait.

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:03.920
Can you tell them what
turkey fried is?

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:04.700
JACQUES PEPIN: Turkey fried?

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:05.250
ANJALI KUMAR: I learned
this earlier.

00:20:05.250 --> 00:20:06.630
JACQUES PEPIN: Turkey
testicles.

00:20:06.630 --> 00:20:08.890
They call it turkey fried.

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:11.730
So the butcher said, well,
let me call the farm.

00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:14.160
So she called the farm and said,
yeah, we can get it, but

00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:16.290
I have to have an inspector
guy, too.

00:20:16.290 --> 00:20:17.545
She said, oh, wait a minute.

00:20:17.545 --> 00:20:19.150
How much is that
going to cost?

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:20.960
He said, well, $0.80 a pound.

00:20:20.960 --> 00:20:22.670
All right, fine.

00:20:22.670 --> 00:20:23.540
Give me three pounds.

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:27.720
So I came back and she said,
I got some of you for you.

00:20:27.720 --> 00:20:29.910
I said, woo hoo, turkey
ball, that's good.

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:32.900
So we fried them and
we gave them.

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:34.760
All the guests didn't
know what it was.

00:20:34.760 --> 00:20:37.900
They said, oh, these sausage
are really good.

00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:42.455
And when we told some of them
what it was, some had to go

00:20:42.455 --> 00:20:44.236
out to throw up but--

00:20:44.236 --> 00:20:46.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:49.270
JACQUES PEPIN: And then Susie,
many years later--

00:20:49.270 --> 00:20:51.580
she lives in Napa Valley now--

00:20:51.580 --> 00:20:55.000
came, and we did the mother of
all Thanksgiving, which again,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.660
I mentioned in that article.

00:20:56.660 --> 00:21:02.330
There was Thomas Keller,
cooking, Cat Cora, Don

00:21:02.330 --> 00:21:06.110
[INAUDIBLE], I mean, a lot of
great chefs, like eight.

00:21:06.110 --> 00:21:08.460
And I think we did eight
different type of turkey.

00:21:08.460 --> 00:21:10.010
There was a split up
and pomegranate

00:21:10.010 --> 00:21:12.630
glazed grilled turkey.

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:14.770
There was a suveed turkey.

00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:15.900
There was a deep fried turkey.

00:21:15.900 --> 00:21:17.640
There was a brine turkey.

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:19.570
There was a regular
roasted turkey.

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:22.520
There was a turkey I did with
Julia, which was bone out,

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:25.610
where I bone out the leg and
roast the breast separately.

00:21:25.610 --> 00:21:27.370
And then the one that I had
in the "New York Times"

00:21:27.370 --> 00:21:31.380
yesterday, which is steamed
first and then roasted after.

00:21:31.380 --> 00:21:34.200
What's was your question?

00:21:34.200 --> 00:21:35.300
About the--

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:37.575
AUDIENCE: Well, it was
what is your favorite

00:21:37.575 --> 00:21:38.485
Thanksgiving tradition.

00:21:38.485 --> 00:21:39.400
But I guess I followed--

00:21:39.400 --> 00:21:39.850
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah,
the turkey.

00:21:39.850 --> 00:21:42.480
AUDIENCE: that with the turkey
balls in New York.

00:21:42.480 --> 00:21:43.710
JACQUES PEPIN: Right.

00:21:43.710 --> 00:21:47.460
I say it's amazing that it was
such a Puritan beginning.

00:21:47.460 --> 00:21:52.300
It became the most probably
dynastic celebration that we

00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:56.040
have here, and the best, because
there is no political

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:58.870
application or religious
application.

00:21:58.870 --> 00:22:01.770
You don't have any gift
to give to anyone.

00:22:01.770 --> 00:22:03.640
There's nothing with
a kid, you know?

00:22:03.640 --> 00:22:06.980
So it's purely the pleasure of
sitting down, overeating and

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:08.080
overdrinking.

00:22:08.080 --> 00:22:10.410
That's great.

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:11.160
ANJALI KUMAR: Yes.

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:12.460
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:22:12.460 --> 00:22:14.730
I wonder if you can provide any
inspiration for working

00:22:14.730 --> 00:22:17.580
parents who are short on time
but still want to provide a

00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:19.750
special meal for
their families.

00:22:19.750 --> 00:22:21.590
JACQUES PEPIN: Well,
very easy.

00:22:21.590 --> 00:22:22.840
You've got to buy my book.

00:22:25.984 --> 00:22:26.970
Not that one.

00:22:26.970 --> 00:22:28.170
Or that one, also,
if you want.

00:22:28.170 --> 00:22:28.570
But I have two books.

00:22:28.570 --> 00:22:29.430
Yes, I did.

00:22:29.430 --> 00:22:30.810
No, it's a good question.

00:22:30.810 --> 00:22:32.480
I did two series
on television--

00:22:32.480 --> 00:22:34.880
not the last one that I have
now-- two series before called

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:38.980
"Fast Food My Way." We did about
26 shows, which is about

00:22:38.980 --> 00:22:42.030
130 recipes.

00:22:42.030 --> 00:22:44.510
So I have "Fast Food My Way" and
"More Fast Food My Way."

00:22:44.510 --> 00:22:46.770
We did two series.

00:22:46.770 --> 00:22:49.180
And the premises was
that probably the

00:22:49.180 --> 00:22:51.190
antiquity of this one.

00:22:51.190 --> 00:22:55.110
The premise was that when you
work in the restaurant, you

00:22:55.110 --> 00:22:57.460
have the prep cook who comes in
the morning, and he bones

00:22:57.460 --> 00:23:00.280
out the chicken, bones out the
fish, slices the mushrooms,

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:02.660
washes the spinach,
chops the shallot.

00:23:02.660 --> 00:23:03.630
You have everything ready.

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:06.340
Nothing is cooked, but
it's ready, fresh.

00:23:06.340 --> 00:23:07.510
So I get behind the stove.

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:09.390
The first order is a filet
of sole or whatever.

00:23:09.390 --> 00:23:09.795
I grab it.

00:23:09.795 --> 00:23:10.350
It's done.

00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:12.620
I put a bit of shallots on top,
some sliced mushroom, a

00:23:12.620 --> 00:23:14.900
dash of white wine, bring
it to a boil.

00:23:14.900 --> 00:23:17.150
Finish it with a piece of
butter, and I do that dish in

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:21.360
five, six minutes because I have
the prep ready for me.

00:23:21.360 --> 00:23:23.860
So I did do those books
with the same idea.

00:23:23.860 --> 00:23:26.850
I used the supermarket
as the prep cook, and

00:23:26.850 --> 00:23:28.660
we can do that now.

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:31.850
So I had two boneless, skinless
breasts of chicken.

00:23:31.850 --> 00:23:32.890
I had prewashed spinach.

00:23:32.890 --> 00:23:34.950
I have a no-stick pan.

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:37.780
I mean, when I did those shows
of 30 minute, which are like

00:23:37.780 --> 00:23:39.350
28 and a half, I did
four dishes, and

00:23:39.350 --> 00:23:40.195
I had nothing prepared.

00:23:40.195 --> 00:23:44.850
I usually did them on time
there, you know?

00:23:44.850 --> 00:23:46.340
You go to the supermarket.

00:23:46.340 --> 00:23:47.780
Now I go to the deli.

00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:49.260
And I take a container.

00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:50.170
It's all the same
price, anyway.

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:52.650
So I take some black olives,
some Kalamata olives, some

00:23:52.650 --> 00:23:56.960
green ones, some [INAUDIBLE],
a little bowl of mozzarella,

00:23:56.960 --> 00:24:00.120
some dried tomato, too, and
I'm making a salad.

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:02.860
I get home to put a bit more
olive oil on top of that, some

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:04.100
fresh basil.

00:24:04.100 --> 00:24:06.510
I buy a package of ham.

00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:10.015
I take a Martini glass, a nice,
honey-cured ham, put a

00:24:10.015 --> 00:24:12.356
big slice of ham hanging
on the side, fill

00:24:12.356 --> 00:24:12.860
it up with my salad.

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:13.770
First course--

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:15.150
fine.

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:17.560
Using this supermarket
in those ways--

00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:18.400
it's true--

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:20.970
with a minimal amount
of effort and still

00:24:20.970 --> 00:24:22.800
have fresh good food.

00:24:22.800 --> 00:24:25.890
Because it's very important to
have the kid partake of what

00:24:25.890 --> 00:24:31.550
you do, to involve the kid, and
all that, and not to give

00:24:31.550 --> 00:24:35.410
the kid the idea that your house
is a restaurant and the

00:24:35.410 --> 00:24:36.580
kid is going to eat
a la carte.

00:24:36.580 --> 00:24:38.150
I don't like this, I
don't like that.

00:24:38.150 --> 00:24:40.080
That didn't exist with
my daughter.

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:41.430
That's what we served tonight.

00:24:41.430 --> 00:24:42.090
That was it.

00:24:42.090 --> 00:24:43.440
That was dinner.

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:46.420
And when Claudine was five years
old, asked her mother,

00:24:46.420 --> 00:24:48.000
my wife, Mom, what's
for dinner?

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:49.740
My wife would say food.

00:24:49.740 --> 00:24:52.760
And it's still food now.

00:24:52.760 --> 00:24:54.070
That's what we have
for dinner.

00:24:54.070 --> 00:24:57.580
We never specify the
type of food.

00:24:57.580 --> 00:24:59.390
No, but try that
type of thing.

00:24:59.390 --> 00:25:01.460
It's good, yeah.

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:03.791
Thank you.

00:25:03.791 --> 00:25:04.960
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:05.865
Thank you for coming here.

00:25:05.865 --> 00:25:07.550
JACQUES PEPIN: Thank you.

00:25:07.550 --> 00:25:10.590
Your voice is very familiar
because I grew up while my mom

00:25:10.590 --> 00:25:12.360
was watching you 24/7.

00:25:12.360 --> 00:25:13.130
JACQUES PEPIN: Oh, thank you.

00:25:13.130 --> 00:25:15.430
AUDIENCE: So a lot of memories
coming back.

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:17.780
So I know this is about cooking,
and your book is

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:20.440
about cooking, and you're all
about cooking, but for us lazy

00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:23.810
New Yorkers, what's your
favorite restaurant in New

00:25:23.810 --> 00:25:26.610
York, and what would
you order there?

00:25:26.610 --> 00:25:29.620
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, it's
a leading question.

00:25:29.620 --> 00:25:33.850
Two days ago, I was in Chinatown
in Flushing.

00:25:33.850 --> 00:25:39.610
And at lunch for $8 or $10,
whatever we spent per person

00:25:39.610 --> 00:25:42.170
in a Shanghai restaurant.

00:25:42.170 --> 00:25:45.180
So there's many, many places
like this that you can eat.

00:25:45.180 --> 00:25:49.210
I have to say, in New York, in
Manhattan, the French Culinary

00:25:49.210 --> 00:25:52.950
Institute, where I am a dean
of the school there

00:25:52.950 --> 00:25:55.930
occasionally, it's one of the
best dinners in New York.

00:25:55.930 --> 00:25:58.980
The food has to be super fresh,
morning, and again

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:01.460
night, because the students at
night start by peeling their

00:26:01.460 --> 00:26:05.020
carrots and stuff, can't even
use the stock, whatever, from

00:26:05.020 --> 00:26:07.190
the morning.

00:26:07.190 --> 00:26:09.390
And we do a lunch--

00:26:09.390 --> 00:26:10.340
I think $30.

00:26:10.340 --> 00:26:14.380
And the five-course dinner
is $41, I think.

00:26:14.380 --> 00:26:17.770
So it's really cheap for New
York, and the food is quite

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:19.300
fresh and good.

00:26:19.300 --> 00:26:21.500
AUDIENCE: Where would
you go tonight?

00:26:21.500 --> 00:26:22.710
JACQUES PEPIN: Tonight.

00:26:22.710 --> 00:26:23.160
I don't know.

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:25.116
Anjali didn't tell me where
she's taking me, so--

00:26:25.116 --> 00:26:26.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:26.820 --> 00:26:28.630
ANJALI KUMAR: Ham sandwiches
at Google.

00:26:28.630 --> 00:26:30.440
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:31.010
I don't know.

00:26:31.010 --> 00:26:34.050
I have to do a book signing
tonight, and I may go back to

00:26:34.050 --> 00:26:36.710
the school, actually,
to have dinner.

00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:37.850
We have very good wine, too.

00:26:37.850 --> 00:26:39.040
Good price.

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:40.760
I mean, there's many, many--

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:45.340
you can look even in the Zagat
and other on the internet.

00:26:45.340 --> 00:26:48.500
I mean, there is 24,000
restaurants in New York.

