It was very much a compliment.

00:27:18.930 --> 00:27:19.580
JACQUES PEPIN: Either way
it's a compliment, yeah.

00:27:19.580 --> 00:27:21.700
ANJALI KUMAR: It's the highest
compliment, some might say.

00:27:21.700 --> 00:27:23.640
Very few people, but
somebody might say.

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:25.733
Those people laughing, those
people would say it.

00:27:25.733 --> 00:27:26.720
Yeah.

00:27:26.720 --> 00:27:28.340
AUDIENCE: So in the US, there's
been a long campaign

00:27:28.340 --> 00:27:30.070
of eliminating fat from food.

00:27:30.070 --> 00:27:32.180
Everything is low
fat and no fat.

00:27:32.180 --> 00:27:35.330
And as a result, a lot of the
food has gotten sweeter to

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:37.010
compensate for the
lack of flavor.

00:27:37.010 --> 00:27:40.130
I read that maybe 80% of the
food in the supermarket now is

00:27:40.130 --> 00:27:41.480
artificially sweetened.

00:27:41.480 --> 00:27:42.390
What do you think
of that trend?

00:27:42.390 --> 00:27:45.150
JACQUES PEPIN: You
can go to 90%.

00:27:45.150 --> 00:27:50.390
There were 2,300 cookbooks
published last year.

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:56.880
In the last 20 years, 25 years,
most of them mine.

00:27:56.880 --> 00:28:03.870
In the last 25 years, 30 years,
we've done over 20,000

00:28:03.870 --> 00:28:06.730
books related to losing
weight and diet.

00:28:06.730 --> 00:28:11.260
And we are now 40% fatter than
30 years ago, so it doesn't

00:28:11.260 --> 00:28:13.940
seem to work.

00:28:13.940 --> 00:28:14.880
I don't know.

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:16.950
I think you can eat whatever
you want, but you can't

00:28:16.950 --> 00:28:17.960
swallow it.

00:28:17.960 --> 00:28:18.560
That's the problem.

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:20.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:22.680
JACQUES PEPIN: But It is true.

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:24.760
And your percentage
is even low.

00:28:24.760 --> 00:28:26.620
It's like 90%.

00:28:26.620 --> 00:28:29.360
Now, the amount of sugar that
you have in something like

00:28:29.360 --> 00:28:33.550
catsup and all that savory stuff
is just amazing, more

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:36.100
than in soda.

00:28:36.100 --> 00:28:37.350
It's really frightening.

00:28:40.570 --> 00:28:42.610
For me, you start with
kid and all that.

00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:44.840
First, you never eat something
you can't recognize.

00:28:44.840 --> 00:28:47.230
It's already a good step.

00:28:47.230 --> 00:28:50.850
And many often, of course, for
most kids, a chicken is

00:28:50.850 --> 00:28:52.440
rectangular with
plastic on top.

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:54.980
It doesn't have any feet and
head, but you still know that

00:28:54.980 --> 00:28:55.940
it's chicken.

00:28:55.940 --> 00:28:58.480
But now I was, I don't know,
somewhere not too long ago,

00:28:58.480 --> 00:28:59.800
and there was a little kid.

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:04.070
And so you move from this to
something less recognizable to

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:07.215
even Cheerios or stuff like
that, cereal, where you look

00:29:07.215 --> 00:29:10.120
on the box, you don't really
know exactly what's in there.

00:29:10.120 --> 00:29:15.670
But now, that kid there where I
was, would ask your mother,

00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:19.290
she wanted to eat the red
box or the green box.

00:29:19.290 --> 00:29:21.810
So now, it goes one
step further.

00:29:21.810 --> 00:29:24.060
The food is recognized just
by the color of the box.

00:29:24.060 --> 00:29:25.410
That's why they have
absolutely no

00:29:25.410 --> 00:29:26.960
idea what's in there.

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:29.460
We have to avoid processed
food at all cost because

00:29:29.460 --> 00:29:33.510
that's really deadly, the junk
that there is in it.

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:37.060
But, of course, on the other
hand, markets are opening.

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:39.790
The markets have never been as
beautiful as they are today.

00:29:39.790 --> 00:29:42.190
When I came to America, there
was only one salad.

00:29:42.190 --> 00:29:44.300
It was iceberg, period.

00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:47.430
No leek, so shallot, no Oriental
vegetable in the

00:29:47.430 --> 00:29:48.260
supermarket.

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:52.350
Now the supermarkets are
absolutely beautiful.

00:29:52.350 --> 00:29:54.230
And people tell me they don't
want to cook anymore.

00:29:54.230 --> 00:29:57.170
So what do they do with the
stuff at the end of the week?

00:29:57.170 --> 00:29:59.350
Someone must buy it.

00:29:59.350 --> 00:30:03.190
Otherwise, they wouldn't
replenish it on Monday.

00:30:03.190 --> 00:30:06.270
So the last few years,
people are cooking.

00:30:06.270 --> 00:30:10.130
And then we are becoming
"localvore." You have to go

00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:12.680
local food now, organic.

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:14.160
And so all that is good.

00:30:14.160 --> 00:30:16.410
It used to be like that
not that long ago.

00:30:16.410 --> 00:30:17.970
I already said, my mother
and my father

00:30:17.970 --> 00:30:20.020
were organic farmers.

00:30:20.020 --> 00:30:22.450
Of course, they had no idea what
the word "organic" meant.

00:30:22.450 --> 00:30:27.190
But the point is that chemical
fertilizer did not exist, and

00:30:27.190 --> 00:30:29.170
fungicides, insecticides,
pesticides

00:30:29.170 --> 00:30:30.720
did not exist either.

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:33.470
So basically we used some cow
manure, whatever we had.

00:30:33.470 --> 00:30:34.960
We did the garden,
and that was it.

00:30:34.960 --> 00:30:37.680
So we're going back to
this, and it's fine.

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:39.400
It's terrific, actuality.

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:43.230
And eating from next-door
farm.

00:30:43.230 --> 00:30:45.310
But then we always exaggerate.

00:30:45.310 --> 00:30:46.010
Here we go.

00:30:46.010 --> 00:30:47.960
And I've been to restaurants
where they

00:30:47.960 --> 00:30:49.040
introduced me to carrot.

00:30:49.040 --> 00:30:49.760
This is a carrot.

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:50.980
Her name is Sarah.

00:30:50.980 --> 00:30:53.100
She went born on the
7th of March.

00:30:53.100 --> 00:30:55.420
Give me the goddamn carrot.

00:30:55.420 --> 00:30:59.180
So we go too far sometimes.

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:01.790
ANJALI KUMAR: That seems
a bit extreme.

00:31:01.790 --> 00:31:02.700
JACQUES PEPIN: But it happens.

00:31:02.700 --> 00:31:04.140
ANJALI KUMAR: So don't go to
that restaurant, whoever was

00:31:04.140 --> 00:31:06.520
asking for the restaurant.

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:09.570
AUDIENCE: So it feels like
there's a lot more TV

00:31:09.570 --> 00:31:11.430
celebrity chefs now, and
the rise of the Food

00:31:11.430 --> 00:31:11.960
Network and all that.

00:31:11.960 --> 00:31:12.150
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:31:12.150 --> 00:31:13.880
AUDIENCE: So I'm just curious
what your opinion of the

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:16.190
current generation
of TV chefs are?

00:31:16.190 --> 00:31:18.075
Are there any that you're
a particular fan of or

00:31:18.075 --> 00:31:19.390
anything like that?

00:31:19.390 --> 00:31:20.670
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, I was--

00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:22.185
I forget where I was.

00:31:22.185 --> 00:31:24.950
I was at a convention
a few weeks ago.

00:31:24.950 --> 00:31:29.520
There was a food historian
saying that there is 407

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:31.860
cookery shows on television.

00:31:31.860 --> 00:31:32.950
That kind of my mind.

00:31:32.950 --> 00:31:35.070
I mean, I don't know whether
it's accurate, frankly.

00:31:35.070 --> 00:31:39.060
But even if there's only 200
or so, it's just amazing.

00:31:39.060 --> 00:31:41.390
But people look at it for
different reasons.

00:31:41.390 --> 00:31:43.570
I'm sure many people look at
my show and say, well, that

00:31:43.570 --> 00:31:44.330
guy's boring.

00:31:44.330 --> 00:31:48.360
All he does is cook, too,
and do and whatever.

00:31:48.360 --> 00:31:50.170
And it's fine.

00:31:50.170 --> 00:31:53.650
Some of the people do Italian
for entertainment, for other

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:56.690
type of thing, and I think the
more it brings people into

00:31:56.690 --> 00:31:58.970
food, the better it is.

00:31:58.970 --> 00:32:02.080
Every year, I go to the Food
and Wine Festival in Aspen.

00:32:02.080 --> 00:32:05.350
Last year was the 30th
anniversary, and I think I did

00:32:05.350 --> 00:32:09.270
it 28 times, many times with
Julia and then even my mother

00:32:09.270 --> 00:32:10.260
when she came.

00:32:10.260 --> 00:32:12.720
So it's 5,000 people there.

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:16.280
Last year, we drank 45,000
bottles of wine from Thursday

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:19.930
until Monday, 5,000 people
there, and about 300 wineries.

00:32:19.930 --> 00:32:22.960
And if you know Aspen, everyone
is kind of very

00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:24.810
cliquish because it's
all closed in there.

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:26.020
No one has a car.

00:32:26.020 --> 00:32:27.230
And it's a great thing.

00:32:27.230 --> 00:32:28.770
Now, everyone is into food.

00:32:28.770 --> 00:32:30.440
Everyone knows you there.

00:32:30.440 --> 00:32:33.240
So people will come to me and
say, I know you had all the

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:34.040
shows on television.

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:35.770
You are the best.

00:32:35.770 --> 00:32:39.110
And the reason those people
say that is that only the

00:32:39.110 --> 00:32:41.000
people who like me
come to see me.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:42.250
The other ones don't.

00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:42.920
They go to--

00:32:42.920 --> 00:32:43.380
I don't know--

00:32:43.380 --> 00:32:45.402
Bobby Flay next door and say,
you know, we look at all of

00:32:45.402 --> 00:32:46.270
the shows on television.

00:32:46.270 --> 00:32:48.860
You are the best,
and so forth.

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:50.340
That way, I think it's fine.

00:32:50.340 --> 00:32:53.080
We all have our own way
of doing things.

00:32:53.080 --> 00:32:54.160
Some people like it.

00:32:54.160 --> 00:32:56.700
Some don't really care
one way or the other.

00:32:56.700 --> 00:33:02.000
And so for me, I don't
really look--

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:04.450
to tell you the truth-- much
at cookery shows on

00:33:04.450 --> 00:33:05.950
television.

00:33:05.950 --> 00:33:07.860
Most of the time I don't.

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:11.580
So I don't really know that
many, but certainly, a show

00:33:11.580 --> 00:33:15.600
like "Hell's Kitchen" or
whatever is certainly not the

00:33:15.600 --> 00:33:20.620
way to train someone in the
kitchen because there is a

00:33:20.620 --> 00:33:25.780
great of love, at the risk
of sounding a bit mushy.

00:33:25.780 --> 00:33:31.150
But cooking, you have to
cook with your gut.

00:33:31.150 --> 00:33:32.960
It's something which
is automatic.

00:33:32.960 --> 00:33:35.770
There is a great deal of
affection of love that you

00:33:35.770 --> 00:33:37.130
bring into what you do.

00:33:37.130 --> 00:33:40.210
And yelling at people your head
off is not going to train

00:33:40.210 --> 00:33:41.470
someone properly.

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:43.880
But I know that this
is television.

00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:44.820
That's the way it is.

00:33:44.820 --> 00:33:47.820
If you go into the kitchen at
Per Se with Thomas Keller, or

00:33:47.820 --> 00:33:51.010
Jean-Georges, or [INAUDIBLE],
there's no noise.

00:33:51.010 --> 00:33:51.965
The chef is there.

00:33:51.965 --> 00:33:52.650
You order.

00:33:52.650 --> 00:33:53.940
We order this, this, this.

00:33:53.940 --> 00:33:55.350
Say, yes, chef, I will do.

00:33:55.350 --> 00:33:56.760
I say pick up this, that, too.

00:33:56.760 --> 00:33:57.360
The guy pick up.

00:33:57.360 --> 00:33:57.530
No noise.

00:33:57.530 --> 00:33:59.280
You hear the cling
of the thing.

00:33:59.280 --> 00:34:00.470
That's all you hear.

00:34:00.470 --> 00:34:01.460
It's very organized.

00:34:01.460 --> 00:34:05.840
It's very structured and
disciplined in a sense, so no

00:34:05.840 --> 00:34:07.120
televisions come there.

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:09.780
There's nothing to film.

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:11.739
You're noticing that
It's really boring.

00:34:11.739 --> 00:34:16.989
So they create those shows,
where everything is hey, man.

00:34:16.989 --> 00:34:21.440
But it's not really the way
it is in a real kitchen.

00:34:21.440 --> 00:34:24.860
And as far as all the shows,
there are some very good chefs

00:34:24.860 --> 00:34:25.929
on television.

00:34:25.929 --> 00:34:30.375
I mean, certainly people like
Lidia Bastianich and Bobby

00:34:30.375 --> 00:34:33.034
Flay or Mario Batali,
I mean, those guys

00:34:33.034 --> 00:34:34.820
are really good chefs.

00:34:34.820 --> 00:34:37.239
I've seen some others who
wouldn't recognize a carrot

00:34:37.239 --> 00:34:40.070
from a potato, but.

00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:41.929
they don't do it for that.

00:34:41.929 --> 00:34:44.300
And often I asked people,
how many people

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:45.750
cook out of a show?

00:34:45.750 --> 00:34:47.020
Not that many, really.

00:34:47.020 --> 00:34:50.894
They look at it for
other things.

00:34:50.894 --> 00:34:53.179
That was your question, right?

00:34:53.179 --> 00:34:55.670
No, his question.

00:34:55.670 --> 00:34:58.360
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering
if you remember the first

00:34:58.360 --> 00:35:01.210
thing you taught your daughter
to cook and what you would

00:35:01.210 --> 00:35:03.930
recommend for someone as like a
first way to introduce their

00:35:03.930 --> 00:35:05.830
children to the kitchen?

00:35:05.830 --> 00:35:07.960
JACQUES PEPIN: To cook with your
daughter, you mean, or

00:35:07.960 --> 00:35:09.340
children in general?

00:35:09.340 --> 00:35:09.590
Yeah.

00:35:09.590 --> 00:35:12.456
They say you have to
get them involved.

00:35:12.456 --> 00:35:16.990
When Claudine was a year
old, I hold her in

00:35:16.990 --> 00:35:18.180
my arm, and we cook.

00:35:18.180 --> 00:35:19.540
She's stirred the pot.

00:35:19.540 --> 00:35:20.440
So she stirred it.

00:35:20.440 --> 00:35:21.610
Quote, she made it.

00:35:21.610 --> 00:35:24.630
And she was going to taste
it, of course.

00:35:24.630 --> 00:35:28.670
And as I said, again,
we don't explain

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:30.010
the menu to the children.

00:35:30.010 --> 00:35:31.960
We cook whatever we cook.

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:36.280
And you find out that the kid
absolutely adores string beans

00:35:36.280 --> 00:35:38.970
for like a month, and then they
hate string beans for

00:35:38.970 --> 00:35:39.890
another month.

00:35:39.890 --> 00:35:42.060
And then they like
this and that.

00:35:42.060 --> 00:35:44.020
Claudine liked-- it ended up
when she was a kid like

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:46.620
artichokes and Brussels sprouts
were like her favorite

00:35:46.620 --> 00:35:49.340
vegetables.

00:35:49.340 --> 00:35:52.230
And also the fact that certainly
she had frog legs

00:35:52.230 --> 00:35:54.980
and escargot, as we are
French, at my house.

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:57.750
And the kids don't
really mind that.

00:35:57.750 --> 00:36:00.400
Usually, very small kids, up to
like age seven, eight, and

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:02.690
they go to school, and they
talk to their friends, and

00:36:02.690 --> 00:36:03.210
say, you eat what?

00:36:03.210 --> 00:36:04.010
Yuck.

00:36:04.010 --> 00:36:05.710
This is still so.

00:36:05.710 --> 00:36:08.750
So you have that type of thing,
that they want to be

00:36:08.750 --> 00:36:11.630
the same than their friend,
and you have

00:36:11.630 --> 00:36:12.580
to go through that.

00:36:12.580 --> 00:36:15.650
I remember taking Claudine
when she was like

00:36:15.650 --> 00:36:16.630
10, 12 years old.

00:36:16.630 --> 00:36:19.290
We always spent a weekend
together in New York, go to

00:36:19.290 --> 00:36:21.430
the theater, or a movie,
and go to a restaurant.

00:36:21.430 --> 00:36:27.840
And I said, OK, you want to
go to see Tonton Andre.

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:32.030
Uncle Andre was Andre Soltner,
the owner of Lutece, here,

00:36:32.030 --> 00:36:33.760
because she knew him.

00:36:33.760 --> 00:36:35.750
One of the greatest restaurants
in New York.

00:36:35.750 --> 00:36:38.840
And I said, it's
your birthday.

00:36:38.840 --> 00:36:42.420
She said can we go to Burger
King or whatever.

00:36:42.420 --> 00:36:45.380
So I said, fine, OK.

00:36:45.380 --> 00:36:47.950
So nothing is wrong,
occasionally, here and there.

00:36:47.950 --> 00:36:51.930
But the kid should be partaking
of the food, being

00:36:51.930 --> 00:36:55.460
part of it, and there is nothing
better for a child

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:58.130
coming back home and listening
in the kitchen.

00:36:58.130 --> 00:37:01.320
The kitchen is the most
comforting place of the house.

00:37:01.320 --> 00:37:05.090
And hearing the cling of the
pots and pans, the smell in

00:37:05.090 --> 00:37:09.170
the kitchen, the voice of your
mother, those smells, those

00:37:09.170 --> 00:37:12.250
sounds, and all of that will
remain with you the

00:37:12.250 --> 00:37:13.060
rest of your life.

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:16.320
It's a very important
comfort zone.

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:17.910
You see that with those kids in

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:19.890
Afghanistan or whatever now.

00:37:19.890 --> 00:37:23.470
What you dream at night,
that type of food, not

00:37:23.470 --> 00:37:24.480
really for the food.

00:37:24.480 --> 00:37:26.870
You want it for the comfort
and what it brings.

00:37:26.870 --> 00:37:31.890
I think it was a Chinese
philosopher Lin Yutang, I

00:37:31.890 --> 00:37:36.990
think, who said the entire
paraphrasing, patriotism is

00:37:36.990 --> 00:37:39.860
the taste of the dishes
you had as a child.

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:42.180
And there is a great deal of
truth in this, because that

00:37:42.180 --> 00:37:44.092
brings so many other things.

00:37:44.092 --> 00:37:44.470
So.

00:37:44.470 --> 00:37:47.710
I don't want to get
too deep here.

00:37:47.710 --> 00:37:50.172
ANJALI KUMAR: Now what
was your question?

00:37:50.172 --> 00:37:51.950
Go ahead.

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:53.870
AUDIENCE: So what is it that
excites you the most about

00:37:53.870 --> 00:37:56.700
what's happening
in food today?

00:37:56.700 --> 00:38:00.660
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, the
involvement of the farm, the--

00:38:00.660 --> 00:38:04.070
yes, the entrees that
people are.

00:38:04.070 --> 00:38:06.270
And that's kind of unique
to America, too,

00:38:06.270 --> 00:38:08.350
to a certain extent.

00:38:08.350 --> 00:38:13.250
Because for many Europeans,
they look at Americans and

00:38:13.250 --> 00:38:14.750
say, those people
eat five dishes.

00:38:14.750 --> 00:38:17.800
This is it-- hot dog, hamburger,
fried chicken,

00:38:17.800 --> 00:38:21.690
pizza, and can of macaroni,
or whatever.

00:38:21.690 --> 00:38:23.840
Which is, of course, not true.

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:25.790
And which is, of course, true.

00:38:25.790 --> 00:38:30.850
If you go into the [INAUDIBLE]
crowd, if you want, that's

00:38:30.850 --> 00:38:34.050
usually where you have a lot of
obese people, and they will

00:38:34.050 --> 00:38:36.530
eat four, five dishes
over and over again.

00:38:36.530 --> 00:38:38.010
That's how people eat.

00:38:38.010 --> 00:38:41.460
But then, conversely, if you
move in any urban center, even

00:38:41.460 --> 00:38:45.140
a small town now, the amount of
restaurants is staggering.

00:38:45.140 --> 00:38:47.300
And the diversity,
because we are a

00:38:47.300 --> 00:38:48.840
country of ethnic people.

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:51.110
For one night, you're going
to eat Turkish.

00:38:51.110 --> 00:38:52.170
Then the day after
is Shanghai.

00:38:52.170 --> 00:38:55.450
Then it may be Italian,
French, Portuguese,

00:38:55.450 --> 00:38:56.250
Greek, and all that.

00:38:56.250 --> 00:38:59.210
And that's the way people eat,
which is absolutely amazing.

00:38:59.210 --> 00:39:03.150
Even for me, I go back to France
now, and after a while,

00:39:03.150 --> 00:39:06.520
I'm bored with the food because
I'm used to more

00:39:06.520 --> 00:39:09.920
diversity and other
things here.

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:15.020
Because if you go to France, the
food is good, and you're

00:39:15.020 --> 00:39:16.320
born with that type of food.

00:39:16.320 --> 00:39:19.370
That's what you eat, so 99%
of people eat French.

00:39:19.370 --> 00:39:21.690
There are Chinese restaurants
and all that, but basically,

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:23.230
I'm talking especially
in the country,

00:39:23.230 --> 00:39:23.980
people will eat French.

00:39:23.980 --> 00:39:25.570
I did the same thing in Italy.

00:39:25.570 --> 00:39:28.230
99.9% of Italians eat
Italian food.

00:39:28.230 --> 00:39:34.100
Same thing with Portuguese, with
Greek, and with Spanish

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:36.240
and so forth, because the
food is good and that's

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:37.590
what you're used to.

00:39:37.590 --> 00:39:39.760
But in America, that's
not the case.

00:39:39.760 --> 00:39:42.590
And you explore in all those
different directions, and it's

00:39:42.590 --> 00:39:44.440
very exciting.

00:39:44.440 --> 00:39:47.450
And good food, too.

00:39:47.450 --> 00:39:47.920
ANJALI KUMAR: Great.

00:39:47.920 --> 00:39:49.130
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes, sir.

00:39:49.130 --> 00:39:51.890
AUDIENCE: So thanks
again for coming.

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:53.690
When you were talking a little
bit about "Hell's Kitchen," I

00:39:53.690 --> 00:39:58.880
was reminded of your memoir,
"The Apprentice." Or was it

00:39:58.880 --> 00:39:59.730
"The Apprenticeship"?

00:39:59.730 --> 00:40:00.510
I apologize.

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:01.300
It's been a few years.

00:40:01.300 --> 00:40:01.925
ANJALI KUMAR: The show on NBC.

00:40:01.925 --> 00:40:03.586
AUDIENCE: But it's
a wonderful book.

00:40:03.586 --> 00:40:03.980
JACQUES PEPIN: Thank you.

00:40:03.980 --> 00:40:06.840
AUDIENCE: And I was trying
to think back to your

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:11.300
descriptions of what it was like
to cook in the old world

00:40:11.300 --> 00:40:15.690
in France and of kind of the
great French chefs, and what

00:40:15.690 --> 00:40:18.200
that apprenticeship was like,
and how it in some ways it

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:20.620
could be pretty brutal.

00:40:20.620 --> 00:40:22.440
And I thought those were kind
of very interesting

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:26.850
descriptions, because we went
through kind of a dead zone of

00:40:26.850 --> 00:40:28.300
cooking, at least in America,
and as you've

00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:29.660
said today, it's back.

00:40:29.660 --> 00:40:30.100
JACQUES PEPIN: Yeah, it's--

00:40:30.100 --> 00:40:33.040
AUDIENCE: So what was all that
like when you were young in

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:37.030
France, coming up, and then
maybe a little bit of what it

00:40:37.030 --> 00:40:40.345
was like when you were kind of
cooking for the government and

00:40:40.345 --> 00:40:40.720
the royalty?

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:43.940
I mean, that whole trajectory
of your career is sort of

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:45.940
unknown to Americans, I guess.

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:46.840
JACQUES PEPIN: Yes.

00:40:46.840 --> 00:40:51.430
Well, from '56 to '59, I was
chef to the President in

00:40:51.430 --> 00:40:53.360
France under the Fourth
Republic.

00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:56.730
The government was changing at
a rapid pace, and I finished

00:40:56.730 --> 00:40:58.820
with de Gaulle in '59.

00:40:58.820 --> 00:41:01.430
And someone introduced me, as
you did, a few weeks ago and

00:41:01.430 --> 00:41:03.630
said that man cooked for three
French presidents.

00:41:03.630 --> 00:41:07.290
Three of them are dead.

00:41:07.290 --> 00:41:10.200
OK, I think one is
still alive.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:11.180
I'm not sure.

00:41:11.180 --> 00:41:16.780
The apprenticeship that I did,
it was another world.

00:41:16.780 --> 00:41:20.590
Interestingly enough, if
I look at my father--

00:41:20.590 --> 00:41:22.180
well, I never knew
my grandfather.

00:41:22.180 --> 00:41:23.780
They all died in the
first World War.

00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:30.120
But my father and other older
people at that time, my

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:32.580
generation it was different
than they were,

00:41:32.580 --> 00:41:34.570
but not that different.

00:41:34.570 --> 00:41:36.580
Remember, there was no planes
here at the time.

00:41:36.580 --> 00:41:38.070
We had no television.

00:41:38.070 --> 00:41:40.800
There was no internet.

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:41.950
It was really--

00:41:41.950 --> 00:41:47.640
barely electricity, so it was
different for my parents.

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:50.310
It was different for me,
but not that different.

00:41:50.310 --> 00:41:54.030
Now, I look at my granddaughter,
wow, In those

00:41:54.030 --> 00:41:55.340
one or two generations.

00:41:55.340 --> 00:41:57.050
I mean, if they look
at my book, it's

00:41:57.050 --> 00:41:58.500
like the Middle Age.

00:41:58.500 --> 00:42:00.280
It's really, really
another world.

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:06.000
Just the management of the
stove, to start with.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:08.650
We had a stove that you start in
the morning, put some paper

00:42:08.650 --> 00:42:11.570
and some wood, then coal,
and you have to

00:42:11.570 --> 00:42:12.550
keep that thing hot.

00:42:12.550 --> 00:42:17.940
Now, those were very large
rectangular stoves, almost as

00:42:17.940 --> 00:42:19.060
big as that stage.

00:42:19.060 --> 00:42:21.790
And there is different-- six
people are working on it,

00:42:21.790 --> 00:42:25.390
three on each side, like the
sous department, the

00:42:25.390 --> 00:42:26.410
fish, and so forth.

00:42:26.410 --> 00:42:27.930
And then in between there
was the oven.

00:42:27.930 --> 00:42:29.680
You open the door on one side.

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:31.730
On the other side, it
was like a funnel.

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:34.200
So there was no thermostat, of
course, or stuff like that.

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:37.540
When that thing really had red
on top, the temperature was

00:42:37.540 --> 00:42:39.570
probably 500 degrees
in the oven.

00:42:39.570 --> 00:42:42.550
And on one side, someone
is cooking a fish.

00:42:42.550 --> 00:42:44.160
I'm cooking a souffle
on the other side.

00:42:44.160 --> 00:42:47.080
So you have to work within the
food itself to move it close

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:49.260
to the door, open the door a
little bit, put a thing in

00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:51.530
front of it to regulate the
temperature and so forth.

00:42:51.530 --> 00:42:55.070
It's not like we put it on the
timer, 20 minutes, 375, go

00:42:55.070 --> 00:42:57.410
take a nap.

00:42:57.410 --> 00:42:59.390
It was totally different
things.

00:42:59.390 --> 00:43:02.170
And that stove was hot.

00:43:02.170 --> 00:43:06.490
Like at the Plaza Athenee in
Paris, still we had no stove.

00:43:06.490 --> 00:43:07.590
The people are coming.

00:43:07.590 --> 00:43:10.500
The lunch crowd come
at 12 o'clock.

00:43:10.500 --> 00:43:12.540
Now, the people in charge of
the stove, which were the

00:43:12.540 --> 00:43:17.330
first [INAUDIBLE], if you did
not regulate it properly, then

00:43:17.330 --> 00:43:20.110
that thing is not lukewarm, but
not really hot enough for

00:43:20.110 --> 00:43:22.895
the first 30 people who come in,
and that pushed back the

00:43:22.895 --> 00:43:24.140
whole dining room.

00:43:24.140 --> 00:43:26.465
When that people came in the
dining room, that stove had to

00:43:26.465 --> 00:43:29.520
be red to where the chef would
be out of his mind.

00:43:29.520 --> 00:43:32.370
So just the management of that
was a great deal of work,

00:43:32.370 --> 00:43:35.290
which, of course, doesn't exist
at all anymore because

00:43:35.290 --> 00:43:37.000
it's another world.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.950
Now, there was no
school, really.

00:43:39.950 --> 00:43:42.650
You worked behind the line
as an apprentice.

00:43:42.650 --> 00:43:45.490
And you were not particularly
well treated.

00:43:45.490 --> 00:43:48.270
If you did something wrong, you
got a kick in the behind.

00:43:48.270 --> 00:43:52.950
And that was not a big deal, but
that's the way things were

00:43:52.950 --> 00:43:56.270
with some people,
not with all.

00:43:56.270 --> 00:43:59.070
But also the fact that they
didn't tell you anything.

00:43:59.070 --> 00:43:59.940
They do a sauce.

00:43:59.940 --> 00:44:01.330
You say, what is that?

00:44:01.330 --> 00:44:01.960
It's a sauce

00:44:01.960 --> 00:44:04.130
[SPEAKING FRENCH], which means nothing.

00:44:04.130 --> 00:44:07.650
Or if the chef tells you to
do this, and you say why--

00:44:07.650 --> 00:44:09.950
first, I would not even
have said why.

00:44:09.950 --> 00:44:12.940
But if I had said why, he said
because I just told you.

00:44:12.940 --> 00:44:14.750
That's about the end
of the explanation.

00:44:14.750 --> 00:44:20.380
So you learn by osmosis,
by stealing the things.

00:44:20.380 --> 00:44:22.020
And there was no recipe.

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:28.130
It was purely memory of
the senses in the

00:44:28.130 --> 00:44:28.300
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:44:28.300 --> 00:44:32.850
sense of the taste, and look,
and smell, and so forth.

00:44:32.850 --> 00:44:35.890
And then for a year, I cleaned
up pots, pans,

00:44:35.890 --> 00:44:37.060
did vegetables, too.

00:44:37.060 --> 00:44:38.730
And one day, the chef
told me, you?

00:44:38.730 --> 00:44:41.740
Tomorrow, you start
at the stove.

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:42.150
Wow!

00:44:42.150 --> 00:44:43.440
I was flabbergasted.

00:44:43.440 --> 00:44:45.140
I said, I don't know.

00:44:45.140 --> 00:44:46.860
I went to the stove, and
I knew how to do it.

00:44:46.860 --> 00:44:49.130
Why did I know how to
do it and remember?

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:50.690
Through that type of osmosis.

00:44:50.690 --> 00:44:55.130
That was a type of
apprenticeship, which is very

00:44:55.130 --> 00:44:55.790
different now.

00:44:55.790 --> 00:44:59.640
But remember, I was 13, 14,
15 years old during my

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:00.150
apprenticeship.

00:45:00.150 --> 00:45:03.070
And it's a way of learning,
which is still applied to a

00:45:03.070 --> 00:45:04.480
certain extent.

00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:07.290
I used to teach skiing in
upstate New York, here.

00:45:07.290 --> 00:45:08.620
That's how I met my wife.

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:10.550
I've been married 47 years.

00:45:10.550 --> 00:45:14.855
So I would teaching skiing.

00:45:14.855 --> 00:45:17.420
I remember for several years,
I taught the kids, middle

00:45:17.420 --> 00:45:19.620
school, or whatever it was,
seven, eight years old, 10

00:45:19.620 --> 00:45:23.310
years old, from a
Catskill school.

00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:26.110
And they would come up to
teach kids how to ski.

00:45:26.110 --> 00:45:28.010
You go up the mountain,
say, stay close to

00:45:28.010 --> 00:45:29.780
me, and you go down.

00:45:29.780 --> 00:45:32.020
If you put them on the line
and talk to them about the

00:45:32.020 --> 00:45:38.170
full line and the position of
your wedge, and all that, it

00:45:38.170 --> 00:45:39.640
comes here, and it
comes out there.

00:45:39.640 --> 00:45:40.790
They want to ski.

00:45:40.790 --> 00:45:45.380
The same weekend, I'm giving
a class to a lawyer, maybe.

00:45:45.380 --> 00:45:49.410
And that person, 30 years old,
to want to know why I'm

00:45:49.410 --> 00:45:52.060
turning, why this, why
the position, too.

00:45:52.060 --> 00:45:54.080
It's a totally different
explanation.

00:45:54.080 --> 00:45:56.190
This is probably
what we do now.

00:45:56.190 --> 00:45:58.680
At the French Culinary Institute
here, we cater to

00:45:58.680 --> 00:45:59.120
the people.

00:45:59.120 --> 00:46:00.480
It costs a fortune.

00:46:00.480 --> 00:46:01.220
We explain.

00:46:01.220 --> 00:46:01.930
We show them.

00:46:01.930 --> 00:46:04.760
We cater to them-- totally
different than when I was an

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:06.080
apprentice.

00:46:06.080 --> 00:46:09.680
When I'm there, sometimes there
is graduation, and often

00:46:09.680 --> 00:46:10.870
I'm a judge.

00:46:10.870 --> 00:46:14.730
I'm amazed, absolutely amazed,
what they can do in the six

00:46:14.730 --> 00:46:15.880
months they have been there.

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:18.270
I would never have been able to
do that after three years

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:19.410
of apprenticeship.

00:46:19.410 --> 00:46:19.750
Never.

00:46:19.750 --> 00:46:22.980
However, I was certainly much
faster with my knife, cleaning

00:46:22.980 --> 00:46:26.240
all kinds of manual things that
you learn through that

00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:28.760
type of endless repetition.

00:46:28.760 --> 00:46:30.580
So a very different way
of learning now

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:33.375
than it used to be.

